        <div class="sbb sb-gold">
          <div class="bi"><span class="bi-ico">â“</span><div><span class="bi-lbl cgo">Detection: </span><span class="bi-txt">How was the UAS first detected? How long from first detection to positive ID? What sensors were most effective?</span></div></div>
          <div class="bi"><span class="bi-ico">â“</span><div><span class="bi-lbl cgo">Decision Speed: </span><span class="bi-txt">Was the Â§130i / Â§124n authority determination made quickly enough? Did the ICC handoff protocol work?</span></div></div>
          <div class="bi"><span class="bi-ico">â“</span><div><span class="bi-lbl cgo">Technique Effectiveness: </span><span class="bi-txt">Did the first mitigation technique work? If not, why not? Autonomous UAS? RF resilient platform?</span></div></div>
          <div class="bi"><span class="bi-ico">â“</span><div><span class="bi-lbl cgo">Urban Constraints: </span><span class="bi-txt">Did civilian presence, infrastructure, or airspace complexity limit options? How can the site plan improve?</span></div></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="kfbar" style="margin:4px 0 0 0;"><span class="kf-lbl">ğŸ“Œ Final Note:</span><span> Every engagement is a training data point. Lessons identified must become lessons learned â€” update your site defense plan, sensor coverage map, and ICC protocols after every incident, drill, and exercise.</span></div>
